        How Brisbane Apartments and Units Are Valued: What Sellers Need to Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Apartments are valued differently from houses, and the factors that drive price are specific enough that sellers who understand them are better positioned to present their property and support a strong result.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling an apartment or unit in Brisbane is a different exercise from selling a house. The valuation methodology, the buyer psychology, and the attributes that drive price premiums are all specific to strata property. Sellers who treat their apartment the same way they would treat a house sale, relying on broad suburb medians and general market commentary, often end up with a less accurate price guide and a less compelling presentation. Understanding how apartments are actually valued in Brisbane gives you a much better foundation for a well-run campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why apartments are valued differently from houses</h2>
      <p>The fundamental reason apartment valuation differs from house valuation is land. When you sell a house in Brisbane, a significant portion of the value is in the land itself. Land is scarce, has intrinsic value, and generally appreciates over time. The building on the land depreciates, but the land underneath it grows in value as the suburb develops.</p>

      <p>In a strata title apartment, individual lot owners share the land. The land content per lot is minimal, and it is not individually owned in the same way as a freehold house. The value of an apartment is therefore driven almost entirely by the attributes of the unit itself: its position in the building, its configuration, its outlook, its inclusions, and the financial health of the body corporate. There is no land premium equivalent to drive price growth independently of those unit-specific factors.</p>

      <p>This has two practical implications for sellers. First, the comparison method is tighter and more specific for apartments: the most relevant comparable is another unit on a similar floor, with similar orientation and parking, in the same or a closely comparable building. A three-bedroom house sale on the other side of the suburb is less useful as a comparable for an apartment than a two-bedroom sale three floors below in the same building. Second, the value drivers are specific and manageable: sellers can directly address car parking, presentation, body corporate documentation, and marketing quality in ways that move the needle on price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The specific attributes that drive Brisbane apartment values</h2>
      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Floor level and outlook</strong> are among the most powerful price drivers for apartments in Brisbane. A high-floor unit with city views, river views, or a clear outlook over parkland commands a significant premium over an equivalent unit on a lower floor with no outlook. The premium can be 10% to 20% or more depending on the building, the view quality, and the floor differential. Sellers on upper floors should ensure the marketing captures the outlook prominently, because it is the feature buyers respond to most viscerally.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Orientation and natural light</strong> matter consistently. North-facing apartments with good natural light in the main living areas are more desirable than south-facing equivalents, because they are lighter, warmer in winter, and more pleasant to live in year-round. In Brisbane's climate, the difference in liveability between a north-facing and south-facing unit of identical size and floor level can be significant, and buyers in the market for more than a few weeks are aware of it.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Car parking</strong> affects both value and buyer pool. A unit with two car spaces is genuinely more desirable than an identical unit with one, and commands a measurable premium. A unit with no car parking limits the buyer pool to those who do not need a car in their daily life, which in most Brisbane suburbs is a minority of buyers. Sellers should confirm the number and size of their allocated car spaces, and ensure their listing makes this clear, because buyers filter on parking before inspecting.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Storage</strong> is a smaller but real factor. A lock-up cage storage space adds convenience and value. A unit with no storage adds a practical negative to the comparison, particularly for buyers who are downsizing from a house and need somewhere to keep items that do not fit in a smaller living space.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Body corporate levies</strong> affect value indirectly through buyer appetite. A high quarterly levy relative to comparable buildings reduces the net return for investors and increases the ongoing holding cost for owner-occupiers. Buyers compare levy amounts when evaluating apartments in a similar price range, and a building with significantly higher levies than its competitors will face questions about what those levies are paying for and whether the money is being well spent. Sellers in buildings with higher levies should be prepared to explain the components clearly, because a levy that is high due to comprehensive building insurance and a fully funded sinking fund is a different story from one that is high due to mismanagement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Building age and its effect on Brisbane apartment values</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's apartment stock includes buildings from multiple eras, and building age has a systematic effect on how buyers and valuers assess them. Older buildings from the 1980s and 1990s often carry a price discount relative to newer stock, reflecting genuine concerns about maintenance requirements, dated specifications, and the potential for defects that are common to that era of construction. Buildings from this period may have original kitchens and bathrooms that require updating, limited storage, narrower car spaces, and in some cases structural or waterproofing issues that have not been fully addressed.</p>

      <p>This does not mean older buildings are unsellable or bad investments, but sellers in older buildings should be realistic about where their property sits in the comparison set. A well-maintained and recently renovated apartment in a 1980s building can present well and command a good price, but it will typically sell at a discount to an equivalent unit in a more recently constructed building with modern specifications, everything else being equal.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How bank valuers assess Brisbane apartments: what sellers need to know</h2>
      <p>When a buyer finances the purchase of a Brisbane apartment, their lender commissions an independent bank valuation. The valuer's role is to provide the lender with a conservative, evidence-based estimate of the property's market value. If the valuation comes in below the agreed sale price, the lender will typically only advance funds up to the valuation figure, leaving the buyer to fund the shortfall from savings or to renegotiate the purchase price.</p>

      <p>Bank valuers assess apartments primarily through the direct comparison method, using the most recent and most similar sales available. For apartments, this means sales within the same building (most relevant) or in closely comparable buildings in the same suburb. Valuers adjust for differences in floor level, orientation, parking configuration, renovation standard, and body corporate position. The adjustments are matters of professional judgement, and different valuers can arrive at different figures for the same property.</p>

      <p>Low bank valuations are more common on apartments than on houses in Brisbane, for two related reasons. First, comparable sales are sometimes limited, particularly in smaller buildings or during periods when not many transactions have occurred. Second, apartment prices can move faster than valuers' databases update, particularly during periods of strong demand, which can leave recent sales evidence looking conservative relative to current market conditions.</p>

      <p>Sellers can reduce the risk of a low valuation affecting their sale by ensuring their agent provides comprehensive comparable sales evidence to support the price, and by being willing to provide access for a valuation quickly and at a time that presents the property well. An agent who has prepared a thorough market analysis and can walk a valuer through the relevant comparable sales is in a stronger position to support the contracted price than one who has not.</p>

